{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "In human cells, recent work has produced high-resolution deletion assays 2, leveraging progress in high-throughput technologies such as RNA interference and CRISPR-based screens 1 to produce detailed maps of gene essentiality in different conditions.",
    "As a result of the cost and complexity of knock-out fitness assays, there is a growing interest in computational methods that can complement the experimental work with in silico prediction of fitness effects.",
    "These computational approaches often employ machine learning combined with information from protein sequence, gene homologies, gene-function ontologies, and protein interaction networks [15] [16] [17] [18] [19].",
    "In the case of metabolic genes, i.e.",
    "those that code for catalytic enzymes in metabolic pathways, Flux Balance Analysis (FBA) is a widely employed method for predicting essentiality 20."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "In human cells, recent work has produced high-resolution deletion assays 2, leveraging progress in high-throughput technologies such as RNA interference and CRISPR-based screens 1 to produce detailed maps of gene essentiality in different conditions.",
